ces of this ideology and demonstrates how families created through open adoption, same-sex parenting, divorce, and plural marriage can be sites of resistance. Drawing from personal experiences as both an adoptive and a biological mother and juxtaposing these autobiographical reflections with critical readings of cultural texts representing multi-mother families, Park advocates a new understanding of postmodern families as potentially queer coalitional assemblages held together by a mixture of affection and critical reflection premised on difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAdoptive parents. 0aFamilies. 0aInterracial adoption. 0aLesbian mothers. 0aMotherhood. 0aNuclear families. 0aQueer theory. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Feminist Philosophy. 4aSociology : Family Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438447186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438447186/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles